Keynesian View of Crises,procapitalist but acknowledged the inherent instability,developped a macroeconomic policy framework to address this
Marxian View of Crises,serve as a necessary part before renewal of accumulation
Schumpeter's View of Crises,against intervention,crises serve as cold showers to allow the economy to renew,agreed with Marx
Student of Economics' Question,not whether or not capitalism is inherently unstable,just whether or how fast the economy recovers from crises
New Economic Thinkers' Response,the system cannot recover from crises on its own,the system needs the state to even produce technological innovation
Heilbroner's Thoughts on Capitalist Crises,pose similar threat to dynastic succession breaks in the Middle Ages,pose an existential threat to the entire capitalist system
categories and specifics of each period of capitalism,organizational structure (family-owned to board of directors),size and character of firms (trading to multibillion companies),technological progress,"appearance, consolidation, and decline of labor unions",legal aspects (move towards LLCs and corporations),methods of engaging the labor (cottage industry to mass production),extent of private ownership (limited to biometric data)
social structure of accumulation,"per David Gordon, this is the siphoning of the surplus to the top social hierarchy"
social structure calls attention to...,"changes in technological, organizational, and ideological conditions needed for capitalism to occur"
"late stage global financial capitalism requires private realm of ownership, Neoliberal ideology, and propaganda narratives for the masses"
process of transcendence,"capitalism exploits all available opportunities of the stage, hits a limit, then transcends the limits"
"major downturns such as Great Depression, 1980s, COVID","portals to a new stage, not just mere breaks or interruptions"
GFC is the end of,financial capitalism
Great Depression,end of small-government capitalism
COVID 19,accelerates beginning of techno capitalism
Schumpeter's view of the end of capitalism,slow slide into bureaucratic socialism,educated young people such as university students call for idealistic reforms,"slowly the people wake up and realize the system is no longer capitalism, but actually socialism"
Smith,the end of capitalism comes from corruption
Mills and Rousseau's view of the end of capitalism,ends with utopian socialism
Marx's view of the end of capitalism,increasing social inequality and alienation causes unrest,revolution as people attempt to better their condition,commonly owned means of production by labor,workers' councils run everything
globalization and the end of capitalism,these visions are made much more likely by anti-globalization movements worldwide
science fiction view of the end of capitalism,security and surveillance state,"technology, legal, authoritarianism, Brave New World, cyberpunk"
Marxist view of monopolies,monopolies are not bad as capitalists are still in competition with other industry's monopolists for a larger share of the national income pie
modern monopolies,pose new challenges due to all-encompassing nature
